    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1976-04-05T18:57:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1976-04-05T18:57:00-05:00" n="343"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d343">
                <head>343. Telegram 81789 From the Department of State to the Embassy in the
                    Philippines, April 5, 1976, 2357Z.<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d343fn1"
                        >Source: National Archives, Record Group 59, Central Foreign Policy Files.
                        Secret; <gloss target="#t_limdis">Limdis</gloss>. Repeated to the <gloss
                            target="#t_mtn">MTN</gloss> Delegation in Geneva and to <gloss
                            target="#t_cincpac">CINCPAC</gloss> in Honolulu. Drafted by Willner,
                        Country Officer for the Philippines; cleared by <persName
                            corresp="#p_edmond-lester-e">Edmond</persName>; and approved by
                            <persName corresp="#p_habib-philip-c">Habib</persName>. The memorandum
                        of conversation is in the <persName corresp="#p_ford-gerald-r"
                            >Ford</persName> Library, National Security Adviser, <gloss
                            target="#t_nsc">NSC</gloss> Staff for East Asia and Pacific Affairs,
                        Convenience Files, Box 10.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d343fn2">The Department of State reported on
                        a meeting between <persName corresp="#p_habib-philip-c">Habib</persName> and
                            <persName corresp="#p_virata-cesar">Virata</persName> that covered
                        economic aspects of the U.S.-Philippines relationship.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1976-04-05T23:57:00+00:00"
                            >April 5, 1976, 2357Z</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>TELEGRAM<lb/>Department of State<lb/>081789</p>
                <p>R 052357Z APR 76</p>
                <p>FM <gloss target="#t_secstate">SECSTATE</gloss> WASHDC TO AMEMBASSY MANILA <lb/>
                    <gloss target="#t_info">INFO</gloss> USDEL <gloss target="#t_mtn">MTN</gloss>
                    GENEVA <lb/>
                    <gloss target="#t_cincpac">CINCPAC</gloss> HONOLULU HI</p>
                <p>STATE 081789</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_limdis">LIMDIS</gloss>
                    <gloss target="#t_cincpac">CINCPAC</gloss> FOR <gloss target="#t_polad"
                        >POLAD</gloss>
                </p>
                <p>E.O. 11652: GDS<lb/>TAGS: ETRD, <gloss target="#t_rp">RP</gloss>
                </p>
                <p>SUBJECT: PHILIPPINE NEGOTIATIONS — MEETING WITH <persName
                        corresp="#p_virata-cesar">VIRATA</persName>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>APRIL 2 FINANCE SECRETARY <persName corresp="#p_virata-cesar"
                            >VIRATA</persName>, AMBASSADORS <persName corresp="#p_vega-wilfredo"
                            >VEGA</persName> AND <persName corresp="#p_suarez-pablo"
                            >SUAREZ</persName>, MET WITH ASSISTANT SECRETARY <persName
                            corresp="#p_habib-philip-c">HABIB</persName>, AMBASSADOR <persName
                            corresp="#p_sullivan-william-h">SULLIVAN</persName> AND DEPUTY ASSISTANT
                        SECRETARY <persName corresp="#p_edmond-lester-e">EDMOND</persName>.
                        FOLLOWING ARE MAIN POINTS OF CONVERSATION. <gloss target="#t_memcon"
                            >MEMCON</gloss> BEING POUCHED.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_virata-cesar">VIRATA</persName> CONFIRMED THAT TAX
                        TREATY APPEARED AGREED SUBJECT TO FINAL REVIEW OF TEXT. <persName
                            corresp="#p_habib-philip-c">HABIB</persName> NOTED THAT TEXTILE
                        CONSULTATIONS NOT SUCCESSFUL BUT SUGGESTED NEW EFFORT AIMED AT TRANSFER
                        BETWEEN TRADITIONAL AND NONTRADITIONAL CATEGORIES.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>REGARDING ECONOMIC NEGOTIATIONS, <persName corresp="#p_habib-philip-c"
                            >HABIB</persName> SAID PHILIPPINE TRADE OFFERS SO FAR DID NOT APPEAR
                        VERY CONCESSIONAL, THAT U.S. APPRECIATED HAVING PHILIPPINE DRAFT ON
                        INVESTMENT AND WOULD REVIEW IT, AND U.S. WOULD EXPLORE POSSIBILITY OF <gloss
                            target="#t_gsp">GSP</gloss> WAIVER. HOWEVER, HE STRESSED THAT BLANKET
                        WAIVER <gloss target="#t_gop">GOP</gloss> SEEKING IS NOT IN THE CARDS AND
                        THAT ESSENTIAL REQUIREMENT FOR AGREEMENT WAS A SATISFACTORY OVERALL PACKAGE
                        THAT THE UNITED STATES COULD ACCEPT AS BEING IN ITS INTERESTS. ASKED HOW HE
                        SAW NEGOTIATIONS PROCEEDING, <persName corresp="#p_habib-philip-c"
                            >HABIB</persName> SAID HE FELT WE WERE IN FIRST STAGE AND THAT AFTER A
                        FEW MORE EXCHANGES WE WOULD PROBABLY WANT TO RECESS AND EACH SIDE CONSIDER
                        THE OTHERS PROPOSALS FOR A PERIOD OF TIME. HE INDICATED THAT WE FELT WE SAW
                        THE SHAPE OF AN ULTIMATE AGREEMENT, BUT THAT IT WOULD TAKE CONSIDERABLY MORE
                        WORK TO ACHIEVE.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>TO <persName corresp="#p_virata-cesar">VIRATA</persName> INQUIRY ON
                        LINKAGE OF ECONOMIC AND BASE TALKS, <persName corresp="#p_habib-philip-c"
                            >HABIB</persName> REPLIED THAT WE VIEWED THEM AS SEPARATE, WITH EACH
                        PROCEEDING ON ITS OWN MERITS. HE THOUGHT THE ECONOMIC NEGOTIATIONS WOULD BE
                        THE MORE DIFFICULT OF THE TWO. BASE TALKS HE FELT SHOULD PRESENT RELATIVELY
                        FEW PROBLEMS, SINCE THE PHILIPPINES RECOGNIZED THE DESIRABILITY OF THE U.S.
                        RETAINING ITS BASES AND THE U.S. RECOGNIZES THE NEED TO MEET REQUIREMENTS OF
                        PHILIPPINE SOVEREIGNTY. HE REJECTED A COMPARISON WITH SPAIN POINTING OUT
                        THAT THE U.S.-PHILIPPINE RELATIONSHIP IS BASED ON A MUTUAL DEFENSE TREATY.
                            <persName corresp="#p_kissinger-henry-a">KISSINGER</persName>
                    </item>
                </list>
            </div>
